---
description: Apply when writing or modifying React components in components/ or app/**/*.tsx.
globs: components/**/*.tsx, app/**/*.tsx
---

# Component conventions

## "use client" directive

Add `"use client"` only when the component uses browser APIs, React state, or
event handlers. Omit it for purely presentational components — they are Server
Components by default.

```tsx
// needs "use client" — uses useState, usePathname
"use client";
import { useState } from "react";

// no directive — no hooks, no events
export default function MetricCard({ label, value }: MetricCardProps) { ... }
```

## Props interface

Always define a named `interface` (not `type`) above the component, named
`<ComponentName>Props`:

```tsx
interface StatusBadgeProps {
  status: Status;
}

export default function StatusBadge({ status }: StatusBadgeProps) { ... }
```

For polymorphic components (e.g. Button), define a `Base<Name>Props` interface
and extend it per variant. Combine into a union type for the component:

```tsx
interface BaseButtonProps { ... }
interface ButtonProps extends BaseButtonProps, Omit<ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>, "children"> { as?: "button"; }
interface LinkButtonProps extends BaseButtonProps { as: "a"; href: string; }
type ButtonComponentProps = ButtonProps | LinkButtonProps;
```

## Exports

Always use `export default function ComponentName`. No named exports for
components. No `const Component = () =>` style.

## Prop destructuring

Destructure props in the function signature, not inside the body:

```tsx
// Correct
export default function Tooltip({ content, children, className = "", position = "top" }: TooltipProps) {

// Avoid
export default function Tooltip(props: TooltipProps) {
  const { content, children } = props;
```

## Optional props

Set defaults in the destructure. Common defaults:

- `className?: string` → default `""`
- `variant?: "primary" | "secondary"` → default `"primary"`
- `position?: "top" | "bottom" | "left" | "right"` → default `"top"`

## children

Type as `React.ReactNode` (or import `ReactNode` from `"react"`).
Never type as `JSX.Element` or `string`.

## Multi-variant class lookups

Use a `Record<>` lookup object rather than chained ternaries when mapping a
prop to a Tailwind class string:

```tsx
// Correct
const variantClasses: Record<Variant, string> = {
  primary: "border border-accent-primary/50 text-accent-primary ...",
  secondary: "text-text-muted hover:text-text-primary ...",
};
const classes = `${baseClasses} ${variantClasses[variant]}`;

// Avoid
const classes = variant === "primary" ? "border ..." : variant === "secondary" ? "text-..." : "...";
```

## Static data outside the component

Define static arrays, maps, and lookup objects outside the component function
so they are not recreated on every render:

```tsx
// Correct — defined once at module level
const navLinks = [
  { label: "Experiments", href: "/" },
  ...
];

export default function Header() { ... }
```

## Guard clauses for undefined

Return a fallback element early rather than wrapping the whole return in a
conditional:

```tsx
if (value === undefined) {
  return <span className="text-sm text-text-muted">—</span>;
}
```

## Icons and SVGs

Use inline SVGs directly. Do not add icon packages (Heroicons, Lucide, etc.).
If an icon comes from a Figma MCP source, use it as-is per the Figma rules in
`design-guidelines.mdc`.

## Analytics attributes

Add `data-analytics-*` attributes to all interactive navigational elements
(`<Link>`, `<button>` used for navigation, `<a>`):

```tsx
data-analytics-event="navigation_click"
data-analytics-surface-type="hub"
data-analytics-surface-name="header"
data-analytics-link-label="experiments"
```

Non-navigational interactive elements (toggle buttons, form inputs) do not
need analytics attributes unless they represent a meaningful user action.

## Figma source reference

The hub design file key is: `9VJTxmBWKgeCDTyJLsYM7I`

Add a `@figma` JSDoc comment directly above the component's props interface
when the component has a confirmed Figma counterpart in the hub design file.
Use the format `@figma FILE_KEY:NODE_ID`:

```tsx
/** @figma 9VJTxmBWKgeCDTyJLsYM7I:223:1337 */
interface HeaderProps { ... }
```

**Scope:** This applies to `components/` only. Prototype-specific components
live in their own Figma files with their own file keys — do not use the hub
file key for those. If a prototype component has a Figma source, add its own
`@figma` comment with the correct file key at the top of that file.

When working on a component that has a `@figma` comment, call
`get_design_context` with the node ID before making visual changes, to verify
against the source design.
